Ophthalmologists pioneer leading research in the field of vision sciences and are working hard to manage the huge challenges eye care units face with increasing backlogs. Proud to support World Sight Day.

 #Loveyoureyes #Worldsightday

On World Sight Day 2021 it is important to remember that Cataracts & uncorrected refractive error are the leading causes of vision impairment. 

An eye test can help detect these as well as serious eye conditions, which may need urgent review by an ophthalmologist. #Loveyoureyes

We are proud to support World Sight Day 2021 with the theme #Loveyoureyes.

We work collaboratively with other organisations to raise awareness of blindness and vision impairment as major international public health issues.

3/3

#Ophthalmology

The strain on ophthalmology services is more pronounced than for other specialties for 2 reasons:

1. Ophthalmology services are concentrated on those aged 75+
2. New treatments have emerged in recent years that have placed greater demand on the ophthalmology workforce.

2/3

As the UK population ages, the number of people living with sight loss is expected to increase by over a third in the next decade, reaching 2.7 million by 2030. 

1/3

Today braille literacy is shaping the lives and opportunities of those who are blind and visually impaired thanks to the work of Louis Braille 

(Source material and artefacts kindly supplied by RCOphth Honorary Curator, Richard Keeler) https://t.co/W4VdeEIrSY
Louis Brailleâ€™s determination to provide opportunities for educating blind and visually impaired people has created a lasting legacy https://t.co/XplheAeP98

In the UK alternatives to braille were introduced before Louisâ€™ system became widespread. Moon is a system of raised shapes similar in shape to the alphabet. The braille system, however, soon became much more widespread https://t.co/UhDwvJj6gn

It took time for the braille system to be adopted widely and accepted by the public. It was only through the support of blind pupils that the Royal Institute of Blind Youth implemented the braille system within its curriculum, following Louis' death

In later life Louis devoted his time to musical scores, something that had, until the braille system was invented, been seen as too difficult for visually impaired people to read. In 1852 Louise Braille passed away just days after his 43rd birthday https://t.co/fejfil0CD7

In 1829 Louise Braille officially published his system with an explanation. The 63 characters made up by his raised dots system denoted all the written signs used by the sighted https://t.co/w48NOQ0hp8

By the age of 15 Louis had reduced Barbierâ€™s 12 dots into six and created a system with individual letters, accents and punctuation, as well as mathematical symbols and musical notations. These individual characters were now the right size to read by fingertips https://t.co/SN6BB5uWER

This system was a welcome experiment in educating those with suffering from visual impairments. However, it proved to be a little too complicated and Louis felt he could radically improve the system to work better for blind people

It was at this school that Louis learned of Captain Charles Barbierâ€™s communication method called â€˜night writingâ€™. This pattern of raised dots and dashes on thick paper enabled Louis and other children to understand words and phrases from the dots grouped together

Following the end of the occupation of France by the Russian Army Louis entered the Royal Institution for Blind Youth in Paris, one of the first schools for blind children in the world https://t.co/i4HTcOC771
Being blind in the 19th century could be life-limiting. Those who were blind often fell into poverty and struggled to gain an education. However, Louis was different
No treatment could save Louisâ€™s damaged eye. The wound became infected and spread to the other eye. At the age of five Louis Braille became completely blind
It was in this workshop that Louis decided to use the tools to try and make holes in leather. The heavy tool slipped from his grasp and wounded Louis in the eye https://t.co/CYZIBSyzS1

The Braille family were saddlers who had been working in the same town for generations. They plied their trade in a family workshop, filled with curious tools that fascinated young children https://t.co/XqgcoibouI
In the small town of Coupvray in France Louis Braille was born on 4 January 1809 https://t.co/xvMNHRa4zf

To mark #WorldBrailleDay hereâ€™s a story of Louise Braille and his invention that has shaped the lives of those who are blind and visually impaired for centuries ğŸ‘‡
